2026-04-21 01:26:46 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Output Cable (+) at port p', 'Control-module red LED wiring (anode/cathode connections)'] hypothesis_explanation='From the continuity test: the control switch itself is good, but its negative terminal is unused and the conductor that should be the switched positive output (labelled “Control Output Cable (+)”) is floating at port p. Meanwhile, PSU + is connected only to the control input +; PSU − is tied to both the control input − and the control output −, and also to the anode of the red indicator LED, whose cathode is left unconnected. \n\nThis means:\n1) The switched positive line from the control module to the load is not connected into the series path at all, so the load module never receives 12 V regardless of switch state. The main lamp therefore cannot turn on.\n2) The red inverted-cables indicator LED is miswired (anode at 0 V, cathode floating), so it can never light, even under cable polarity reversal.\n\nThus the fault is a wiring/configuration error inside the control module involving the Control Output Cable (+) at port p and the red LED connections. Repair should reconnect the switch so that it properly inserts between the PSU + (control input +) and the Control Output Cable (+), and correctly wire the LED with its resistor across the 12 V and 0 V lines with the intended polarity.'
